threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, version 1 (ARM), statically linked, stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is an IoT botnet malware, likely a Mirai variant. It exhibits worm-like behavior by attempting to spread to other devices via Telnet. The malware contains a large, hardcoded list of common and default credentials (e.g., root/vizxv, admin/admin, support/support) in function `sub_cf08`, which it uses for brute-force attacks. Upon successful compromise, it uses `wget`, `tftp`, and `curl` to download and execute additional payloads. The sample also includes defensive mechanisms, such as modifying its OOM score via `/proc/self/oom_score_adj` to prevent termination and executing a shell command to kill competing processes. The presence of a Telegram URL (`t.me/disconnect`) further suggests C2 communication or status reporting capabilities.
